<handout>
  <title>Exam 1 - Fall 2024</title>

<section>
<title>Topics</title>

    <p>1.1-1.7
    </p>

    <p>
      Be sure to try each question before looking at the solutions.
    </p>

  <exercises xml:id="exercises-f24exam1">
    <title>Questions</title>

<exercise xml:id="exam1-f24-q1">
<statement>
   An object's height above the ground is recorded at various times. <xref ref="ObjectHeightExam1F24q1"/> gives the object's height
   <m>
     s(t)
   </m>
   (measured in meters) at time
   <m>
     t
   </m>
   (measured in seconds). 

  <table xml:id="ObjectHeightExam1F24q1" >
        <title>An object's height <m>s(t)</m> measured at various times <m>t</m>.</title>
    <tabular halign="center" bottom="minor" top="minor">
      <row header="yes">
        <cell><p><m>t</m> (meters)</p></cell>
        <cell><p><m>s(t)</m> (seconds)</p></cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell><p>0</p></cell>
        <cell><p>35</p></cell>
      </row>
            <row>
        <cell><p>1</p></cell>
        <cell><p>24</p></cell>
      </row>
            <row>
        <cell><p>2</p></cell>
        <cell><p>15</p></cell>
      </row>
            <row>
        <cell><p>3</p></cell>
        <cell><p>8</p></cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell><p>4</p></cell>
        <cell><p>3</p></cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell><p>5</p></cell>
        <cell><p>0</p></cell>
      </row>
    </tabular>
  </table>
<ol marker="(a)">
  <li>
    <p>
      Calculate the average velocity
      <m>
        AV_{[1,3]}
      </m>
      of the object between times
      <m>
        t=1
      </m>
      and
      <m>
        t=3
      </m>
      seconds.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Calculate the average velocity
      <m>
        AV_{[3,5]}
      </m>
      of the object between times
      <m>
        t=3
      </m>
      and
      <m>
        t=5
      </m>
      seconds.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Using a central difference, estimate the value of
      <m>
        s'(3)
      </m>
      . Be sure to include units. Then, use a sentence to explain the meaning of this value in this context.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Do you think
      <m>
        s''(t)
      </m>
      is positive, negative, or zero on
      <m>
        (0,5)
      </m>
      ? Why?
    </p>
  </li>
</ol>
</statement>
<answer>
<ol marker="(a)">
  <li>
    <p>
      <m>AV_{[1,3]} = \frac{8-24}{3-1} = -8</m> meters per second
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      <m>AV_{[3,5]} = \frac{0-8}{5-3} = -4</m> meters per second
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      <m>s'(3) \approx \frac{s(4)-s(2)}{4-2} = \frac{3-15}{2} = -6</m> meters per second.  This estimates the instantaneous velocity of the object at time <m>t=3</m> seconds.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      <m>s'(t)</m> is increasing (becoming less negative) so <m>s''(t)</m> is positive.
    </p>
  </li>
</ol>
</answer>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exam1-f24-q2">
<statement>
        The height
        <m>
          h(V)
        </m>
        (measured in meters) of a given volume
        <m>
          V
        </m>
        of water in a tank (measured in liters) is measured as the tank is filled.
        <ol marker="(a)">
          <li>
            <p>
             What are the units of the derivative
              <m>
                h'(V)
              </m>
              ?   
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The value
              <m>
                h'(V)
              </m>
              is always positive. Why? 
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Carefully sketch a diagram illustrating the shape of a tank for which
              <m>
                h''(V) =0
              </m>
              .
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
</statement>
<answer>
  <ol marker="(a)">
    <li>
      <p>
        meters per liter
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        As the volume <m>V</m> increases, so does the height <m>h(V)</m> of water in the tank.  So <m>h(V)</m> is increasing.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        The sides of the tank should be vertical so that the rate at which the height increases with respect to volume remains constant.  A cylinder works for this.  
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="basic-cylinder">
  <caption>
    A cylinder with circular top and bottom faces and vertical sides.
  </caption>
  <image xml:id="FigCylinder" width="50%">
    <latex-image>
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1]
  % top ellipse
  \draw (0,2) ellipse (1.5 and 0.4);
  % sides
  \draw (-1.5,2) -- (-1.5,0);
  \draw ( 1.5,2) -- ( 1.5,0);
  % bottom ellipse
  \draw[dashed] (-1.5,0) arc (180:360:1.5 and 0.4);
  \draw (1.5,0) arc (0:180:1.5 and 0.4);
\end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
  </image>
</figure>
    </li>
  </ol>
</answer>
 </exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exam1-f24-q3">
<statement>
 The graph of the piecewise-defined function
 <m>
     f
 </m>
 is shown in <xref ref="F24Ex1q3"/>. The graph has a vertical tangent line at
 <m>
     x=-2
 </m>
 and horizontal tangent lines at
 <m>
     x=-3
 </m>
 and
 <m>
     x=-1
 </m>
 . What are all values of
 <m>
     x
 </m>
 ,
 <m>
     -4 &lt; x &lt; 3
 </m>
 at  which
 <m>
     f
 </m>
 is continuous but not differentiable?
 <figure xml:id="F24Ex1q3">
  <caption> Where is <m>f</m> continuous but not differentiable?</caption> 
  <image source="images/DifferentiabilityFall2024Exam1.jpg" width="50%">
        <description>Graph of a piecewise function with a curved segment from x approximately equal to -4 to x = 0 ending at an open circle near (0, 1), a filled point at (0, 2), a line segment descending to (1, 0), and a line segment rising from (1, 0) to the right.
</description>
      </image>
</figure>
</statement>
<choices  randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p><m>x=-2</m> and <m>x=1</m></p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct.  Note the vertical tangent at <m>x=-2</m> and the cusp at <m>x=1</m>.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p><m>x=1</m></p>
      </statement>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p><m>x=-2</m> and <m>x=0</m></p>
      </statement>
    </choice>

     <choice>
      <statement>
        <p><m>x=0</m> and <m>x=1</m></p>
      </statement>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exam1-f24-q4">
<statement>
 Consider the function
 <md>
     f(x) = \begin{cases}2x-2\amp \text{if }x &lt; 3\\ 2x-4 \amp \text{if }x \geq 3.\end{cases}
 </md>
 Let
 <m>
     f
 </m>
 be the piecewise-linear function defined above. Which of the following statements are true?
 <blockquote>
     <p>
         <ol marker="I.">
             <li>


                     <m>\displaystyle \lim_{h \rightarrow 0^-}\frac{f(3+h)-f(3)}{h}=2</m>

             </li>

             <li>

                     <m>\displaystyle \lim_{h \rightarrow 0^+}\frac{f(3+h)-f(3)}{h}=2</m>
             </li>

             <li>

                     <m>\displaystyle f'(3)=2</m>
             </li>
         </ol>
     </p>
 </blockquote>
</statement>
<choices  randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>II only</p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct.  Note that <md> <mrow> \frac{f(3+h)-f(3)}{h} \mathstrut \amp = \frac{2(3+h)-2-[2(3)-4]}{h} </mrow> <mrow> \amp = \frac{2h+2}{h} \text{ for } h &lt; 0 </mrow> </md>
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>None of these statements are true.</p>
      </statement>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>I and II only</p>
      </statement>
    </choice>

     <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>I, II, and III</p>
      </statement>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exam1-f24-q5">
<statement>
 On which interval(s) is
 <m>
     f(x)
 </m>
 increasing based on the graph of
 <m>
     f'(x)
 </m>shown in <xref ref="F24Ex1q5"/>?     
 <figure xml:id="F24Ex1q5">
  <caption> Where is <m>f</m> increasing?  This is the graph of <m>f'</m>.</caption> 
  <image source="images/GraphOffprimeBFall2024Exam1.jpg" width="50%">
        <description>Graph of a smooth wave-like curve crossing the x-axis at x = 0, 2, 4, and 6, with a local minimum near x = 1, a local maximum near x = 3, and another local minimum near x = 5.
</description>
      </image>
</figure>
</statement>
<choices  randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p><m>
            (2,4)
        </m> </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct.  This is where <m>f'</m> is above the horizontal axis.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p><m>
            (1,3) \cup (5,6)
        </m></p>
      </statement>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p><m>
            (0,3)
        </m></p>
      </statement>
    </choice>

     <choice>
      <statement>
        <p><m>
            (0,2) \cup (4,6)
        </m></p>
      </statement>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exam1-f24-q6">
<statement>
Evaluate the following limit:
<md>
    \lim_{x \rightarrow 4}\frac{x^{2}-8x+16}{x-4}
</md>
</statement>
<choices  randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p><m>
           0
        </m> </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct.  <m> \displaystyle \lim_{x \rightarrow 4} \frac{(x-4)(x-4)}{x-4} = \lim_{x \rightarrow 4} x-4 = 0</m>
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p><m>
           8
        </m></p>
      </statement>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p><m>
            -8
        </m></p>
      </statement>
    </choice>

     <choice>
      <statement>
        <p><m>
            \infty
        </m></p>
      </statement>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>Does not exist</p>
      </statement>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exam1-f24-q7">
<statement>
If
<m>
    f(x) = 2+|x-3|
</m>
for all
<m>
    x
</m>
, then the value of
<m>
    f'(2)
</m>
is
</statement>
<choices  randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p><m>
           -1
        </m> </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct.  Graph this function and look at the slope at <m>x=2</m>.
          </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p><m>
           0
        </m></p>
      </statement>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p><m>
            1
        </m></p>
      </statement>
    </choice>

     <choice>
      <statement>
        <p><m>
            2
        </m></p>
      </statement>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>nonexistent</p>
      </statement>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exam1-f24-q8">
<statement>
 The graph of
 <m>
     f
 </m>
 is shown in <xref ref="F24Ex1q8"/>. Which of the following could be the graph of
 <m>
     f'
 </m>
 ?     
 <figure xml:id="F24Ex1q8">
  <caption> The graph of <m>f</m>.</caption> 
  <image source="images/GraphOffFall2024Exam1.jpg" width="50%">
        <description>Graph of a smooth curve rising from below the x-axis, crossing the x-axis left of the y-axis, reaching a maximum above the axis near the y-axis, then crossing the x-axis again before descending below the axis toward b.
</description>
      </image>
</figure>
</statement>
<choices  randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
<!-- <figure xml:id="F24Ex1q8A">
  <caption> </caption> -->
  <image source="images/GraphOffAFall2024Exam1.jpg" width="50%" margins="0% 50%">
        <description>Graph of a smooth curve starting at the x-axis at a, rising to a hump above the axis, crossing the x-axis just to the right of the y-axis, dipping to a valley below the axis, and returning to the x-axis at b.
</description>
      </image>
